1b. Compute a 95% prediction interval for the first forecast using \(\hat{y}\) \(\pm\) 1.96\(s\) where \(s\) is the standard deviation of the residuals. Compare your interval with the interval produced by R.

As the forecast is 98816.41 and \(\sigma\) is 10308.58, the 95% prediction interval can be calculated as 98816.41 - 1.96 * 10308.58 = 78611 and 98816.41 + 1.96 * 10308.58 = 119021, which are exactly what are listed in the model’s summary.

2. Write your own function to implement simple exponential smoothing. The function should take arguments y (the time series), alpha (the smoothing parameter \(\alpha\)) and level (the initial level \(l_0\)). It should return the forecast of the next observation in the series. Does it give the same forecast as ses()?

custom_ses <- function(ts, alpha, l0) {
  N <- length(ts)
  y_hat = c(l0, 0 * (2:N))
  for (j in 1:(N-1)) {
    new <- alpha * ts[j] + (1 - alpha) * y_hat[j]
    y_hat[j+1] = new
  }
  return(y_hat)
}
ts <- pigs
tail(custom_ses(ts, 0.2971, 77260.0561),1)
[1] 98102.32

Using the \(\alpha\) and \(l_0\) found by the ses function, my custom SES function - which is an implementation of the weighted average form - returned roughly the same answer.

3. Modify your function from the previous exercise to return the sum of squared errors rather than the forecast of the next observation. Then use the optim() function to find the optimal values of \(\alpha\) and \(l_0\). Do you get the same values as the ses() function?

custom_rss <- function(par, ts) {
  # ensure alpha parameter is bounded between 0 and 1
  alpha = plogis(par[1])
  l0 = par[2]
  
  N = length(ts)
  fit = custom_ses(ts, alpha, l0)
  res = ts - fit
  
  out = sum(res^2)/(N-1)
  return(out)
}
# optim-based estimates; alpha is first parameter, level is second parameter
est = optim(par = c(0.1, 5000), fn = custom_rss, ts=ts)
alpha = plogis(est$par[1])
l0 = est$par[2]
# ses estimates
ses.fit <- ses(ts)
cbind(ses = ses.fit$model$par, custom = c(alpha, l0))
               ses       custom
alpha 2.971488e-01 2.972525e-01
l     7.726006e+04 7.725105e+04

As shown in the table above, the optimal \(\alpha\) and \(l_0\) values from my custom SES model and the ses function were very similar.

For bonus points, here is a plot comparing the fitted values of the two SES models.

# fit ses model to data

6d. Calculate a 95% prediction interval for the first forecast for each series, using the RMSE values and assuming normal errors. Compare your intervals with those produced using ses and holt.

pb_rmse_lo <- fcast.pb$mean[1] - 1.96 * acc.pb[2]

The prediction intervals calculated using the RMSE were tighter than those generated by the ses and hw functions.

7. For this exercise use data set eggs, the price of a dozen eggs in the United States from 1900–1993. Experiment with the various options in the holt() function to see how much the forecasts change with damped trend, or with a Box-Cox transformation. Try to develop an intuition of what each argument is doing to the forecasts.

[Hint: use h=100 when calling holt() so you can clearly see the differences between the various options when plotting the forecasts.]

Which model gives the best RMSE?

plot(eggs)

# basic model (undamped, additive)
fcast.h <- holt(eggs, damped = FALSE, seasonal="additive", h=100)
autoplot(eggs) + autolayer(fcast.h, series="HW undamped")

# damped model
fcast.hd <- holt(eggs, damped = TRUE, seasonal="additive", h=100)
autoplot(eggs) + autolayer(fcast.hd, series="HW damped")

# Box-Cox transformed undamped model

# Box-Cox transformed damped model

autoplot(eggs) + autolayer(fcast.hbd, series="HW damped with Box-Cox")

# undamped exponential model

Without dampening, the Holt model reasonably projects a negative trend - however, it goes below 0, which doesn’t make practical sense. Dampening seems to provide a flat naive forecast. A Box-Cox transformation reduces error, but with dampening, the RMSE is the same as with the base model, which has no dampening.

The model with the lowest RMSE was actually the undamped exponential.

11c. Why is multiplicative seasonality necessary here?

It’s necessary because the seasonal variance is increasing over time.

11d. Forecast the two-year test set using each of the following methods:

11di. ETS model:

v.ets <- ets(v.train)

11dii. ETS model applied to a Box-Cox transformed series

lambda <- BoxCox.lambda(v.train)

11diii. seasonal naive

11div. STL decomposition applied to the Box-Cox transformed data followed by an ETS model applied to the seasonally adjusted (transformed) data.

# Box-Cox transformation
v.bc <- BoxCox(v.train, lambda=lambda)
v.stl <- stl(v.bc, s.window="periodic")
# seasonally adjust transformed data
v.sa <- seasadj(v.stl)
# back-transform data
v.sa <- (lambda * v.sa + 1)^(1/lambda)
# build and forecast ETS model
v.sa.ets <- ets(v.sa, lambda=lambda)

func.sa.ets <- function(y, h) {
  l <- BoxCox.lambda(y)
  bc <- BoxCox(y, lambda=l)
  bc.stl <- stl(bc, s.window="periodic")
  bc.sa <- seasadj(bc.stl)
  bt.sa <- (l * bc.sa + 1)^(1/l)
  sa.ets <- ets(bt.sa, lambda=l)
  forecast(sa.ets, h=h)
}
cv.sa.ets <- tsCV(visitors, func.sa.ets, h=1)
sqrt(mean(cv.sa.ets^2, na.rm=TRUE))
[1] 43.63903
